# Migrating `EventProcessor` to .NET 8

## Key Problems with the Original Code

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 8 — it was removed entirely.
2. **`Thread.Interrupt()` is obsolete** and unreliable (it only interrupts from managed blocking states).
3. **Race condition**: multiple enqueues between `WaitOne`/`Reset` can lose items — only one `Dequeue` per signal.
4. **No graceful shutdown** mechanism.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _processTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _processTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Graceful shutdown
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel closed.");
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();           // Signal no more items
        _cts?.Cancel();                       // Cancel if draining isn't desired

        var waitTime = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (_processTask is not null)
            await _processTask.WaitAsync(waitTime);
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item)
    {
        // Your processing logic here
    }
}
```

## If You Need a Synchronous API (drop-in replacement)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop) { IsBackground = true };
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        try
        {
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts!.Token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _queue.Add(item);

    public void Stop()
    {
        _queue.CompleteAdding();       // Drain remaining items
        _cts?.Cancel();               // Or cancel immediately
        _thread?.Join(5000);
        // No Thread.Abort — the token handles cancellation
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _queue.Dispose();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { }
}
```

## Migration Pitfalls Summary

| .NET Framework Pattern | .NET 8 Replacement | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` | `Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `CancellationToken` | Obsolete, unreliable |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` | `Channel<T>` or `BlockingCollection<T>` | Thread-safe, no race conditions |
| `while(true)` + manual signal | `await foreach` / `GetConsumingEnumerable` | Cleaner, cancellation-aware |
| `Thread` for background work | `Task.Run` | Better pool utilization, async-friendly |

## Choosing Between the Two Approaches

- **`Channel<T>`** (recommended): fully async, backpressure support, works with `async`/`await` throughout your stack.
- **`BlockingCollection<T>`**: synchronous drop-in, useful when callers can't be made async.

Both fix the original race condition where multiple rapid enqueues could cause `InvalidOperationException` on an empty queue.
